# Renames
dat.new <- dat.rs %>%
  rename("case.id" = "ma", "gender" = "a1", "age" = "a2", 
         "mari.statu" = "a3", "edu.level" = "a4", "main.earn" = "a5",
         "income" = "a6", "occupation" = "a7", 
         "year.work" = "b1", "hour.work" = "b2", "duty.hour.n" = "b3x1k",
         "duty.hour.d" = "b3x2k", "main.posi" = "b5",
         "sick.last.mth" = "c1", "day.sickleave" = "c3",
         "self.evaluate" = "c4", "job.satis" = "c5") %>%
  mutate(age.group = cut(age, breaks = c(-1, 24, 34, 44, 100)),
         age.group = fct_recode(age.group,
                                "1" = "(-1,24]", "2" = "(24,34]", 
                                "3" = "(34,44]", "4" = "(44,100]")) %>%
  mutate(effort = e1 + e2 + e3 + e4 + e5 + e6,
         reward = e7 + e8 + e9 + e10 + e11 + e12 + e13 + e14 + e15 + e16,
         over = o1 + o2 + o3 + o4 + o5 + o6,
         friend = m1 + m2 + m3 + m4 + m5 + m6,
         esteem = e7 + e8 + e9 + e14,
         promotion = e10 + e13 + e15 + e16,
         security = e11 + e12,
         er.rate = effort/reward*10/6,
         ee.rate = effort/esteem*4/6,
         ep.rate = effort/promotion*4/6,
         es.rate = effort/security*2/6) %>%
  print(dat.new)

    ESI = es.rate > 1,

    EE.high = ee.rate > median(ee.rate),
    EP.high = ep.rate > median(ep.rate),
    ES.high = es.rate > median(es.rate),
    direct.p = main.posi == 2, 
    Gender = as.factor(gender),
    Gender = factor(Gender, 
                    labels = c("Male", "Female")),
    
    job.dissatis = job.satis == 2,
    young = age < 28,
    poor.self.rate = self.evaluate == 1,
    iso.group = cut(friend, breaks = c(-1, 15, 19, 100)),
    iso.group = fct_recode(iso.group,

                           "friendly" = "(19,100]"),
    over.work = hour.work > 50,
    live.spouse = mari.statu == 2,
    Income = as.numeric(income),
    income.low = income < median(income),
    Education = factor(edu.level),
    # edu.inter = edu.level == 1,
    # edu.college = edu.level == 2,
    # edu.uni = edu.level == 3,
    duty.hour.n = ifelse(is.na(duty.hour.n), 0, duty.hour.n),
    duty.hour.d = ifelse(is.na(duty.hour.d), 0, duty.hour.d),
    Breadwinner = as.factor(main.earn),
    Breadwinner = factor(Breadwinner, labels = c("Yes", "No")),

Kendalls Tau and Spearmans rank correlation coefficient assess statistical associations based on the ranks of the data. Ranking data is carried out on the variables that are separately put in order and are numbered.

Kendalls Tau: usually smaller values than Spearmans rho correlation. Calculations based on concordant and discordant pairs. Insensitive to error. P values are more accurate with smaller sample sizes. Kendall seems to be a robust way.

However, the Factor Analysis normally use pearson correlation. Pearson also is appropriate for a large sample (>100) Since this studys objective is not to find a suitable method We decide to use Pearson which is better fit our objective of using FA.

### Combine matrix
table1s <- cor.mat.p.ero

# Delete the diagonal
diag(table1s) = ""
# Delete the upper part
table1s[upper.tri(table1s)] <- ""


### Calculate the p-value to combine the Table 1S
p.ero <- corr.test(dat.ero,
                   use = "complete",
                   method = "pearson",
                   adjust = "holm")
# We apply the adjustment for multiple tests 
# See p.adjust for details about why to use "holm" rather than "bonferroni"

p.mat.p.ero <- round(p.ero$p, 3)

# Delete the diagonal
diag(p.mat.p.ero) = ""
# Replace p<0.001
p.mat.p.ero = ifelse(p.mat.p.ero==0, "<0.001", p.mat.p.ero)
# Delete the lower part
p.mat.p.ero[lower.tri(p.mat.p.ero)] <- ""

### Combine matrix
table1s[upper.tri(table1s)] <- p.mat.p.ero[upper.tri(p.mat.p.ero)]

# Produce the p-value matrix (upper triangle)
write.csv(table1s, file = "table1s.csv")

### Run EFA

The built-in function factanal() performs maximum likelihood (ML) factor analysis. However, as the sample correlation matrix is singular, ML factor analysis cannot be used. The function fa() in the package psych offers various factor extraction methods including ML factor analysis, unweighted least squares (ULS), weighted least squares (WLS), generalized least squares (GLS), principal axes factoring (PAF).
The default factor extraction method (minres) finds an ULS solution, and can be used when the covariance or correlation matrix is singular.

# h2: the amount of variance in the item/variable explained by the (retained).
# factors. It is the sum of the squared loadings, a.k.a. communality.
# u2: 1 - h2. residual variance, a.k.a. uniqueness.
# com: Item complexity. Basically it tells you how much an item reflects a # single construct. It will be lower for relatively lower loadings.

Next is rotation promax

efa.ero_32 <- fa(dat.ero, nfactors = 3, rotate = promax, # fm = ml, n.obs = 172) efa.ero_32

Next is varimax

efa.ero_33 <- fa(dat.ero, nfactors = 3, rotate = varimax, # fm = ml, n.obs = 172) efa.ero_33

Then, we run fa with 4 factors, no rotation, use Mximum Likelihood

efa.ero_41 <- fa(dat.ero, nfactors = 4, rotate = none, # fm = ml, ) efa.ero_41

Next is varimax

efa.ero_43 <- fa(dat.ero, nfactors = 4, rotate = varimax, # fm = ml, n.obs = 172) efa.ero_43
